[[File:Baines 1835-Mule spinning crop.jpg|thumb|Part of an 1835 engraving showing a mule scavenger at work]]
'''Scavengers''' were employed in 18th and 19th century in [[cotton mill]]s, predominantly in the UK and the United States, to clean and recoup the area underneath a [[spinning mule]]. The [[cotton]] wastage that gathered on the floor was seen as too valuable for the owners to leave and one of the simplest solutions was to employ young children to work under the machinery. Many children suffered serious injuries while under the mules, with fingers, hands, and sometimes heads crushed by the heavy moving parts. Legislation introduced in 1819 tried to reduce working hours and improve conditions but there were still deaths recorded well beyond the middle of the 19th century.
==Job description== Scavengers were the lowliest of the apprentices at the cotton mills and had to endure the worst conditions.<!--{{POV|date=September 2011}}--> They were employed to work under the machinery to clean up the dust and oil and to gather the cotton that had been thrown off the mule by its intense vibrations. The tenters would not stop to allow the scavenger to work because they were paid by how much they could produce. As the mule moved forwards the children were sent under the machine, sweeping and gathering the cotton. They had to then time their retreat so as to not become entangled within the many moving parts.<ref name="TR">[[Tony Robinson|Robinson, Tony]]. ''[[The Worst Jobs in History]]''. Pan. {{ISBN|0-330-43857-3}} pp. 164–166.</ref> These children had started in the mills at around the age of four, working as scavengers until they were eight before progressing to the role of piecers. They worked 14 to 16 hours a day, beaten if they fell asleep, until they were 15.<ref>[http://www.cottontimes.co.uk/childreno4.htm Children of the Revolution] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817164123/http://www.cottontimes.co.uk/childreno4.htm |date=17 August 2010 }}. Cotton Times. Accessed 2 September 2011.</ref><!-- Both tertiary sources that have introduced inaccuracies. Cotton Times is a good starting point, but heavily redacted-->
==Danger== The job is noted as being one of the worst in history owing to the conditions the children had to work in. The danger of being beneath the machines meant that they had to constantly pay attention to its movements in order to avoid serious injury.<ref>[http://www.yourdiscovery.com/history/worst_jobs/georgian/index.shtml The Worst Jobs in History]. [[Discovery Channel]]. Accessed 2 September 2011.</ref> An 1840 novel by [[Frances Trollope]] describes the work of a scavenger: {{quotation|The miserable little creature... was a little girl about seven years old, whose office as "''scavenger''," was to collect incessantly from the machinery and from the floor, the flying fragments of cotton that might impede the work. In the performance of this duty, the child was obliged, from time to time, to stretch itself with sudden quickness on the ground, while the hissing machinery passed over her; and when this is skilfully done, and the head, body, and outstretched limbs carefully glued to the floor, the steady-moving, but threatening mass, may pass and repass over the dizzy head and trembling body without touching it. But accidents frequently occur; and many are the flaxen locks, rudely torn from infant heads, in the process.|Frances Trollope, ''The life and adventures of Michael Armstrong, the factory boy''<ref>Trollope, Frances Milton. ''The life and adventures of Michael Armstrong, the factory boy''. 1840.</ref>}}
While there were no requirements for factory owners to keep any records about the majority of accidents on their premises there are many anecdotal cases of scavengers suffering serious and sometimes fatal injuries. Some lost fingers or a hand, others are said to have been decapitated.<ref name="AV">Venning, Annabel. [http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1312764/Britains-child-slaves-New-book-says-misery-helped-forge-Britain.html Britain's child slaves], ''[[Daily Mail]]''. 17 September 2010. Accessed 3 September 2011.</ref> A record held at the [[Quarry Bank Mill]], now a museum, states: {{quotation|On the 6th of March 1865 a very melancholy accident befell a lad named Joseph Foden about 13 years of age. While engaged sweeping under a Mule his head was caught between the Roller beam and the carriage&nbsp;– as the latter was putting up&nbsp;– and completely smashed, death being instantaneous.<ref name="TR" />}}
Research by [[Jane Humphries]], a professor of economic history at the [[University of Oxford]], revealed that a mill near Cork had such a poor safety record that six people died and 60 others were mutilated over a four-year period.<ref name="AV" /><!-- This cannot be verified from Daily Mail report. Which mill Overtons, Allmans who. I don't have access to Humphries book to investigate further--> [[Robert Blincoe]], a scavenger who went on to found his own cotton-spinning business, described the life of a [[child labour]]er in his book ''A Memoir of Robert Blincoe''. He wrote about the mistreatment of workers at the cotton mills and the poor conditions that they had to endure. He claims that on one occasion he was nearly crushed by the machine and that, despite the injuries to his head, he was beaten for not completing the sweep in a single turn.<ref>{{citation | title = The Lion | volume = I | year = 1828 | first = Richard | last = Carlile | pages = 189–190}}.</ref>
==Legislation== The children were sent to the mills of Derbyshire, Yorkshire and Lancashire from the [[workhouse]]s in London and other towns and cities in the south of England. About half of the workers in Manchester and Stockport cotton factories surveyed in 1818 and 1819 had begun work at under ten years of age. Part of the [[Factory Acts#Factory Act 1802|Factory Act of 1802]] was introduced to improve conditions for children, but it was not enough. In the [[Factory Acts#Cotton Mills, etc. Act 1819|1819 Cotton Mills and Factories Act]] the law was updated to state that no children under the age of nine were to be employed and that children aged 9–16 years were limited to a maximum day of 16 hours.<ref name="earlyfactory">[http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/transformingsociety/livinglearning/19thcentury/overview/earlyfactorylegislation/ Early factory legislation]. [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament.uk]]. Accessed 2 September 2011.</ref> The law was difficult to enforce, but by 1835 the share of the workforce under 18 years of age in cotton mills in England and Scotland had fallen to 43%.<ref>Galbi, Douglas. [http://www.galbithink.org/child.htm Child Labor and the Division of Labor in the Early English Cotton Mills]. 13 June 1994. Accessed 2 September 2011.</ref> Children were still working in cotton mills throughout the 19th century and, while numerous acts of Parliament were introduced to cut down the hours and improve conditions,<ref>Turner, William. [http://www.cottontown.org/page.cfm?pageid=458&language=eng Child Labour] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615004940/http://www.cottontown.org/page.cfm?pageid=458&language=eng |date=15 June 2011 }}. Cotton Town. Accessed 3 September 2011.</ref> those under the age of 14 were allowed to work in factories until the [[Education Act 1918|Education Act of 1918]] made attending school compulsory.<ref>[http://www.vam.ac.uk/moc/childrens_lives/education_creativity/education_england/index.html Education Legislation in England since 1800]. [[V&A Museum of Childhood]]. Accessed 3 September 2011.</ref>
==References== {{reflist|colwidth=24em}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}
[[Category:Child labour]] [[Category:Obsolete occupations]] [[Category:History of the textile industry]] [[Category:Industrial Revolution in England]]

'''Otto Sverdrup Engelschiøn''' (30 October 1902 – 8 May 1982) was a Norwegian marketer, businessperson, resistance member and genealogist.
He was born in [[Oslo|Kristiania]] as a son of consul-general Søren Dass Brodtkorb Sverdrup Engelschiøn (1867–1909) and Janka Hansen (1869–1935). In 1928 he married Gudrun Irgens Garmann.<ref name=hvem>{{cite encyclopedia|year=1973|title=Engelschiøn, Otto Sverdrup |encyclopedia=[[Hvem er hvem?]]|editor=Steenstrup, Bjørn|publisher=Aschehoug|location=Oslo|url=http://runeberg.org/hvemerhvem/1973/0139.html |page=139|language=Norwegian|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref>
Engelschiøn [[examen artium|finished]] his secondary education in 1922 and graduated from the [[University of Oslo|Royal Frederick University]] with the [[cand.jur.]] degree in 1926. He was an attorney from 1927, and also director of I. Sverdrup Engelschiøn which had the rights to distribute Swedish [[Tomten (company)|Tomten]] products in Norway. In 1929 it was merged with [[Norsk Barnengens Tekniske Fabrik]]. Engelschiøn spent the rest of his career in the company, from 1929 as director of the sales and marketing department and from 1948 to 1968 as co-owner.<ref name=hvem/>
In the 1930s he was a member of [[Nasjonal Samling]]. He left the party in the 1937 party split, continuing though in the ''[[Ragnarok (national socialist group)|Ragnarok]]'' group around national socialist [[Hans S. Jacobsen]], and edited the magazine [[Ragnarok (periodical)|''Ragnarok'']] in 1940.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nazister ble motstandsmenn|date=11 July 2001|work=[[Dagbladet]]|page=39|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Emberland |first=Terje |author2=Rougthvedt, Bernt |title=Det ariske idol: Forfatteren, eventyreren og nazisten Per Imerslund |year=2004 |publisher=Aschehoug |location=Oslo |language=Norwegian |isbn=978-82-03-22964-0 |oclc=58648278}}</ref> In 1940, however, Norway was [[Operation Weserübung|invaded]] and [[occupation of Norway by Nazi Germany|occupied by Nazi Germany]]. Engelschiøn joined the resistance movement and was the head of intelligence in [[Milorg]]'s District 13, Division 3 ([[Asker]] and [[Bærum]]) from 1943 to 1945. He received the [[Defence Medal 1940–1945]] with rosette.<ref name=hvem/>
Engelschiøn chaired the [[Norwegian Genealogical Society]] from 1957 to 1968, and thereafter served as deputy chairman. He was also a [[bibliophile]], chairing [[Bibliofilklubben]] twice as well as the contest jury for the Most Beautiful Book of the Year. Engelschiøn also issued a crime novel under pseudonym.<ref name=hvem/>
He resided in Bærum.<ref name=hvem/> He died in 1982 and was buried at [[Haslum Church|Haslum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disnorge.no/gravminner/index.php?language=engelsk|title=Cemeteries in Norway|publisher=DIS-Norge|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref>
